Narrative 1: User Enters the Depict URL in Their Browser
The journey begins the moment a user types https://hconsult.helioho.st into their browser's address bar and presses Enter.
DNS Resolution. The browser first needs to find out where hconsult.helioho.st lives on the internet. It queries a DNS resolver — usually provided by the user's ISP or a service like Cloudflare — which returns the IP address of the Heliohost server where the Depict application is hosted. This takes milliseconds and is often cached from a previous visit.
TCP Connection and TLS Handshake. The browser opens a TCP connection to that IP address on port 443 (HTTPS). Before any application data flows, the browser and the Heliohost server negotiate a TLS session — they exchange certificates, agree on an encryption cipher, and establish a shared secret key. From this point on, all traffic between the user's machine and the server is encrypted. The user sees the padlock icon in their browser's address bar.
HTTP Request for index.html. With the secure connection established, the browser sends an HTTP GET request for /. The Depict server — a compiled Rust binary using the Hyper web framework, running as a process on the Heliohost server — receives this request. It has no routing logic to speak of: it simply looks up / in its dist/ directory and serves index.html, a small file of around 1,473 bytes. The response comes back with an HTTP 200 status and the HTML content.
Parsing index.html and Discovering Assets. The browser parses the HTML. It is a short document generated by Trunk, Depict's build tool. In the <head>, the browser finds a set of <link> tags that declare everything the page needs before it can run:

A stylesheet: index-597d90855083f957.css (in this case, an empty file — the app is currently unstyled)
Three JavaScript modules via rel="modulepreload": the main wasm-bindgen glue file (depict-web-1aa7b945e8c0be7b.js, ~41 KB) and two Dioxus runtime snippets (dioxus-interpreter-js.../inline0.js at ~12 KB, and dioxus-web.../inline0.js at ~0.3 KB)
The WebAssembly binary via rel="preload" as="fetch": depict-web-1aa7b945e8c0be7b_bg.wasm (~4.9 MB)

Every one of these <link> tags carries an integrity attribute containing a SHA-384 hash. These are Subresource Integrity (SRI) declarations — a security mechanism that tells the browser: "I expect this file to have exactly this cryptographic fingerprint. If it doesn't match, refuse to execute it." Chrome enforces this strictly; Firefox is more lenient.
Parallel Asset Fetching. The browser fires off HTTP requests for all of these assets in parallel, again over the same encrypted connection to the Heliohost server. The Rust server streams them back. The three JS files arrive quickly. The Wasm binary takes a moment longer — at 4.9 MB it is the largest file — and the browser receives it as a stream of 65 KB chunks.
SRI Verification. As each file arrives in full, the browser computes its SHA-384 hash and compares it against the value declared in index.html. If any hash mismatches, the resource is blocked before it can be executed. On Heliohost, all hashes match and all files are accepted.
JavaScript Module Execution. In the <body>, index.html contains a single inline <script type="module">. Once the browser has fetched and verified all the preloaded modules, it executes this script. It imports the wasm-bindgen initialisation function from the JS glue file and calls init(), passing the path to the Wasm binary.
WebAssembly Instantiation. The browser attempts WebAssembly.instantiateStreaming() — a fast path that compiles the Wasm binary while it is still being downloaded. On Heliohost, the Wasm file is not served with the application/wasm MIME type, so the browser falls back to WebAssembly.instantiate(), which waits for the full binary before compiling. Either way, the V8 (Chrome) or SpiderMonkey (Firefox) JavaScript engine compiles the Wasm bytecode into native machine code for the user's CPU. This compilation happens on a background thread.
Dioxus Initialisation. With the Wasm module instantiated, the wasm-bindgen glue calls into the Rust code. The Rust main() function runs inside the Wasm sandbox. wasm_logger::init() wires up the Rust logging infrastructure to the browser console. Then Dioxus initialises its virtual DOM, mounts the application component tree onto the <div id="main"> element in the page, and registers event listeners for user interactions (clicks, inputs). The browser console receives the log messages "Starting up" and "rebuilding app".
The Page is Live. From the user's perspective, the browser tab title updates, the Depict interface appears, and the status indicator shows green: Ready. The total elapsed time from pressing Enter to seeing the interface is typically one to three seconds on a fast connection, dominated by the Wasm download and compilation time. The Rust application is now running natively inside the user's browser tab, in a sandboxed WebAssembly environment, communicating with the DOM through the JavaScript bridge that wasm-bindgen and Dioxus provide.

Narrative 2: User Pastes a Diagram Description and Sees the Result
The application is now live in the user's browser. Everything that follows happens without any further network requests to the Heliohost server — Depict is a fully client-side application. The server's job is done.
The User Pastes Input. The user clicks into the text input box on the Depict interface and pastes a diagram description written in valid Depict syntax. The browser fires a DOM input event. Dioxus registered a listener for this event during initialisation; the wasm-bindgen bridge catches it on the JavaScript side and calls into the Rust/Wasm code.
State Transition: Ready → Processing. Inside the Wasm sandbox, the Rust event handler receives the new input text. The Dioxus component updates its state: the application transitions from Ready to Processing. Dioxus diffs the virtual DOM — it sees that the status indicator component needs to change colour and label — and passes a minimal set of DOM patch instructions to dioxus-interpreter-js, which applies them to the real DOM. The user sees the indicator turn yellow and the label change to "Processing".
Diagram Parsing. The Rust code parses the pasted text according to Depict's syntax rules. This is pure computation inside the Wasm sandbox — no network, no file I/O, no operating system calls. The parser runs on the user's own CPU, inside the browser process, entirely in memory.
Diagram Rendering. If parsing succeeds, the rendering pipeline runs. The parsed diagram description is transformed into a visual representation — coordinates, shapes, connections, labels. This is again pure Rust computation inside the Wasm sandbox, running at near-native speed because the Wasm bytecode was compiled to native machine code during the instantiation step.
Virtual DOM Update. When rendering completes, the Rust code updates the Dioxus component state with the new diagram output and transitions the application state back to Ready (or to Error if rendering failed). Dioxus runs its diffing algorithm, computes the minimal set of changes needed to update the displayed diagram, and hands those patches to dioxus-interpreter-js. The interpreter applies them to the real DOM — updating SVG elements, canvas content, or whatever representation Depict uses for its output.
The User Sees the Diagram. The browser's rendering engine repaints the affected portion of the page. The status indicator returns to green. The diagram appears in the output area. The entire round-trip — from paste to rendered output — involves no network traffic whatsoever. It is bounded only by the speed of the user's CPU and the complexity of the diagram. Simple diagrams update in milliseconds.
If Something Goes Wrong. If the Depict syntax is invalid, the parser returns an error. The Rust error handler sets the application state to Error with an associated message, and transitions the status indicator to red with the label "Failed to render diagram". Dioxus diffs and patches the DOM accordingly. The user sees the red indicator and, if a message is provided, an explanation of what went wrong. No crash, no page reload — the Wasm sandbox remains live and the user can correct their input and try again.

The Boundary Between the Two Narratives
What makes this architecture notable is where the work splits. Everything in the first narrative — DNS, TCP, TLS, HTTP, file serving — involves multiple physical machines and network infrastructure crossing the public internet. The Heliohost server is doing real work under load.
Everything in the second narrative happens on a single machine: the user's own computer, inside a single browser process, inside a WebAssembly sandbox that has no network access and no file system access. The 4.9 MB Wasm binary that took most of the first narrative to deliver contains the entire Depict application — parser, renderer, UI logic — compiled from Rust into a portable binary format that runs identically on Windows, macOS, and Linux, in Chrome, Firefox, and Safari, without any plugins or installations. Once delivered, Heliohost is completely out of the picture.
